        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Ran the audit. Now what?</h4>
            <p>Get a <strong>free SEO audit</strong> in 24 hours — Screaming Frog-grade technical findings plus the content and keyword opportunities that will actually move rankings. No sales call, no obligation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Get my free audit <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">24-hour delivery · No card</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs Screaming Frog — different jobs, often paired</h2>
        <p>We are not in the same category. We work alongside Screaming Frog for many WordPress clients. Read the comparison first so you understand which problem each tool solves.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Capability</th><th>Screaming Frog</th><th>theStacc</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td class="cell-yes">Free (Paid ~$259/yr)</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Technical SEO crawling</td><td class="cell-yes">Industry standard</td><td>Audit included in onboarding</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Identifies issues</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes — every issue</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Fixes the issues</td><td class="cell-no">No — diagnostic only</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes, we apply fixes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Keyword research</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">Topic + cluster planning</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Content production</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">Monthly publishing cadence</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes to your CMS</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">WordPress · Webflow · Ghost</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">GBP posts included</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Rank tracking</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">Built-in</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Recommended setup</strong></td><td colspan="2">Run Screaming Frog quarterly for audits + use theStacc for content and fixes — they pair perfectly</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Screaming Frog wins:</strong> identifying technical SEO issues. Nothing else competes for that one job. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> fixing the issues, writing the content, and publishing the work. Most serious SEO setups run both.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Screaming Frog?</h2>
        <p>Screaming Frog SEO Spider is a desktop crawler — a downloadable application for Windows, macOS, and Ubuntu — that crawls websites the way Googlebot does. It launched in 2010 from a small SEO consultancy in the UK and has become the <strong>industry-standard tool for technical SEO audits</strong>. Estimated active install base is in the hundreds of thousands; the company remains lean and bootstrapped.</p>

        <p>The crawler does dozens of things; the most-used ones are:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Broken link detection</strong> — internal and external 404s, redirect chains, redirect loops</li>
          <li><strong>Meta tag auditing</strong> — missing/duplicate titles, descriptions, H1s, canonicals</li>
          <li><strong>Schema validation</strong> — structured data extraction and Google rich-result validation</li>
          <li><strong>Robots.txt + sitemap checks</strong> — disallowed URLs, missing pages, hreflang errors</li>
          <li><strong>JavaScript rendering</strong> — paid feature, crucial for SPAs and Next.js sites</li>
          <li><strong>Custom extraction</strong> — pull arbitrary data via XPath, CSS, or regex (paid)</li>
          <li><strong>Integrations</strong> — Search Console, Analytics, PageSpeed Insights, Majestic, Ahrefs</li>
          <li><strong>Scheduled crawls</strong> — automated weekly/monthly audits (paid)</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Screaming Frog is <em>not</em>: a fix-it tool, a content platform, a keyword research tool, a rank tracker, or a backlink analyser. It crawls. It reports. Everything after that is human work.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Screaming Frog was founded in 2010 in Henley-on-Thames, UK. The company is <strong>bootstrapped and remains a small team</strong> built around the SEO Spider product, a Log File Analyser, and consulting. The lean structure is why the tool stays focused and price increases are rare — the founders have explicitly resisted VC funding and feature bloat for over a decade.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Screaming Frog features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is enormous for a desktop application. Here is what matters in daily use.</p>

        <h3>1. The crawl itself</h3>
        <p>Enter a URL. Screaming Frog crawls every linked page, asset, and resource — exactly the way Googlebot would. Free version stops at 500 URLs. Paid version is unlimited (technically bounded by your machine's RAM). On a modern laptop a 100,000-URL crawl is comfortable; bigger sites need RAM tuning or breaking into segments.</p>

        <h3>2. Issue detection</h3>
        <p>Every crawl surfaces issues grouped by severity:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Response codes</strong> — 4xx errors, 5xx errors, redirect chains, redirect loops</li>
          <li><strong>Page titles + meta descriptions</strong> — missing, duplicate, too long, too short</li>
          <li><strong>H1/H2</strong> — missing, duplicate, multiple H1s per page</li>
          <li><strong>Canonicals</strong> — missing, non-indexable, canonical chains</li>
          <li><strong>Images</strong> — missing alt text, oversized files, broken image URLs</li>
          <li><strong>Robots + indexability</strong> — disallowed URLs, noindex flags, sitemap orphans</li>
          <li><strong>Hreflang</strong> — missing return tags, conflicts, invalid language codes</li>
          <li><strong>Core Web Vitals</strong> — pulled from PageSpeed Insights API</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This list is genuinely exhaustive. Sitebulb has nicer explanations; Screaming Frog has more checks.</p>

        <h3>3. JavaScript rendering (paid)</h3>
        <p>Crucial for any modern stack. The paid version renders pages with a Chromium-based headless browser before extracting content — meaning it sees what Google sees on React, Vue, Angular, Next.js, Astro hybrid renders, and other JavaScript-heavy sites. The free version is HTML-only and will silently miss most of your content.</p>

        <h3>4. Custom extraction (paid)</h3>
        <p>Pull arbitrary data from any crawled page using XPath, CSS selectors, or regex. Common use cases: extract author names, publish dates, product prices, schema fields, or any custom HTML attribute. This is the feature SEO consultants use most often after the standard checks.</p>

        <h3>5. Integrations</h3>
        <p>Connect Google Search Console, Google Analytics, PageSpeed Insights, Majestic, Ahrefs, and Moz. The crawler then overlays click data, traffic, and backlink metrics onto every crawled URL. Turns the crawler into a one-pane analysis tool — extremely useful for content audits ("which pages have impressions but no clicks?").</p>

        <h3>6. Scheduled crawls (paid)</h3>
        <p>Automate weekly or monthly crawls with email exports. Essential for agencies monitoring 10+ clients. Not as polished as Lumar's cloud scheduling, but built-in and free with the license.</p>

        <h3>7. The Log File Analyser (separate product)</h3>
        <p>Different product at the same price (~$259/yr). Analyses Googlebot's actual server logs to show which pages Google crawls and how often. Genuinely useful for big sites managing crawl budget; overkill for most.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">⚠️ What it does not do</div>
          <p>No content production. No keyword research. No backlink analysis. No rank tracking. No CMS publishing. No fix-it automation — you get a list of issues; you (or a developer) fix them by hand. The audit is the first 10% of the work, not the last 10%.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="pricing">Screaming Frog pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>Screaming Frog publishes simple pricing. There is no tier ladder — it is free or paid.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
